=> {[33m:so_question_title[0m=>[31m[1;31m"[0m[31mWhy is it faster to process a sorted array than an unsorted array?[1;31m"[0m[31m[0m,
 [33m:so_question_body[0m=>
  [31m[1;31m"[0m[31m<div class=[1;35m\"[0m[31mpost-text[1;35m\"[0m[31m itemprop=[1;35m\"[0m[31mtext[1;35m\"[0m[31m>[1;35m\r[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\r[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Here is a piece of C++ code that seems very peculiar. For some strange reason, sorting the data miraculously makes the code almost six times faster.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre class=[1;35m\"[0m[31mlang-cpp prettyprint-override[1;35m\"[0m[31m><code>#include &lt;algorithm&gt;[1;35m\n[0m[31m#include &lt;ctime&gt;[1;35m\n[0m[31m#include &lt;iostream&gt;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31mint main()[1;35m\n[0m[31m{[1;35m\n[0m[31m    // Generate data[1;35m\n[0m[31m    const unsigned arraySize = 32768;[1;35m\n[0m[31m    int data[arraySize];[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    for (unsigned c = 0; c &lt; arraySize; ++c)[1;35m\n[0m[31m        data[c] = std::rand() % 256;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    // !!! With this, the next loop runs faster[1;35m\n[0m[31m    std::sort(data, data + arraySize);[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    // Test[1;35m\n[0m[31m    clock_t start = clock();[1;35m\n[0m[31m    long long sum = 0;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    for (unsigned i = 0; i &lt; 100000; ++i)[1;35m\n[0m[31m    {[1;35m\n[0m[31m        // Primary loop[1;35m\n[0m[31m        for (unsigned c = 0; c &lt; arraySize; ++c)[1;35m\n[0m[31m        {[1;35m\n[0m[31m            if (data[c] &gt;= 128)[1;35m\n[0m[31m                sum += data[c];[1;35m\n[0m[31m        }[1;35m\n[0m[31m    }[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    double elapsedTime = static_cast&lt;double&gt;(clock() - start) / CLOCKS_PER_SEC;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m    std::cout &lt;&lt; elapsedTime &lt;&lt; std::endl;[1;35m\n[0m[31m    std::cout &lt;&lt; [1;35m\"[0m[31msum = [1;35m\"[0m[31m &lt;&lt; sum &lt;&lt; std::endl;[1;35m\n[0m[31m}[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>Without <code>std::sort(data, data + arraySize);</code>, the code runs in 11.54 seconds.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>With the sorted data, the code runs in 1.93 seconds.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Initially, I thought this might be just a language or compiler anomaly. So I tried it in Java.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre class=[1;35m\"[0m[31mlang-java prettyprint-override[1;35m\"[0m[31m><code>import java.util.Arrays;[1;35m\n[0m[31mimport java.util.Random;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31mpublic class Main[1;35m\n[0m[31m{[1;35m\n[0m[31m    public static void main(String[] args)[1;35m\n[0m[31m    {[1;35m\n[0m[31m        // Generate data[1;35m\n[0m[31m        int arraySize = 32768;[1;35m\n[0m[31m        int data[] = new int[arraySize];[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m        Random rnd = new Random(0);[1;35m\n[0m[31m        for (int c = 0; c &lt; arraySize; ++c)[1;35m\n[0m[31m            data[c] = rnd.nextInt() % 256;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m        // !!! With this, the next loop runs faster[1;35m\n[0m[31m        Arrays.sort(data);[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m        // Test[1;35m\n[0m[31m        long start = System.nanoTime();[1;35m\n[0m[31m        long sum = 0;[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m        for (int i = 0; i &lt; 100000; ++i)[1;35m\n[0m[31m        {[1;35m\n[0m[31m            // Primary loop[1;35m\n[0m[31m            for (int c = 0; c &lt; arraySize; ++c)[1;35m\n[0m[31m            {[1;35m\n[0m[31m                if (data[c] &gt;= 128)[1;35m\n[0m[31m                    sum += data[c];[1;35m\n[0m[31m            }[1;35m\n[0m[31m        }[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m        System.out.println((System.nanoTime() - start) / 1000000000.0);[1;35m\n[0m[31m        System.out.println([1;35m\"[0m[31msum = [1;35m\"[0m[31m + sum);[1;35m\n[0m[31m    }[1;35m\n[0m[31m}[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>With a somewhat similar but less extreme result.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>My first thought was that sorting brings the data into the cache, but then I thought how silly that is because the array was just generated.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>What is going on?</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>Why is a sorted array faster to process than an unsorted array?</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>The code is summing up some independent terms, and the order should not matter.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m    </div>[1;31m"[0m[31m[0m,
 [33m:so_answer_body[0m=>
  [31m[1;31m"[0m[31m<div class=[1;35m\"[0m[31mpost-text[1;35m\"[0m[31m itemprop=[1;35m\"[0m[31mtext[1;35m\"[0m[31m>[1;35m\r[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>You are a victim of <a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branch_predictor[1;35m\"[0m[31m>branch prediction</a> fail.</strong></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<h2>What is Branch Prediction?</h2>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Consider a railroad junction:</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Entroncamento_do_Transpraia.JPG[1;35m\"[0m[31m><img src=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//i.stack.imgur.com/muxnt.jpg[1;35m\"[0m[31m alt=[1;35m\"[0m[31m[1;35m\"[0m[31m></a>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<sub><a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Entroncamento_do_Transpraia.JPG[1;35m\"[0m[31m>Image</a> by Mecanismo, via Wikimedia Commons. Used under the <a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/deed.en[1;35m\"[0m[31m>CC-By-SA 3.0</a> license.</sub></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Now for the sake of argument, suppose this is back in the 1800s - before long distance or radio communication.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>You are the operator of a junction and you hear a train coming. You have no idea which way it is supposed to go. You stop the train to ask the driver which direction they want. And then you set the switch appropriately.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><em>Trains are heavy and have a lot of inertia. So they take forever to start up and slow down.</em></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Is there a better way? You guess which direction the train will go!</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>If you guessed right, it continues on.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>If you guessed wrong, the captain will stop, back up, and yell at you to flip the switch. Then it can restart down the other path.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>If you guess right every time</strong>, the train will never have to stop.<br>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<strong>If you guess wrong too often</strong>, the train will spend a lot of time stopping, backing up, and restarting.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>Consider an if-statement:</strong> At the processor level, it is a branch instruction:</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><img src=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//i.stack.imgur.com/pyfwC.png[1;35m\"[0m[31m alt=[1;35m\"[0m[31menter image description here[1;35m\"[0m[31m></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>You are a processor and you see a branch. You have no idea which way it will go. What do you do? You halt execution and wait until the previous instructions are complete. Then you continue down the correct path.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><em>Modern processors are complicated and have long pipelines. So they take forever to [1;35m\"[0m[31mwarm up[1;35m\"[0m[31m and [1;35m\"[0m[31mslow down[1;35m\"[0m[31m.</em></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Is there a better way? You guess which direction the branch will go!</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>If you guessed right, you continue executing.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>If you guessed wrong, you need to flush the pipeline and roll back to the branch. Then you can restart down the other path.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>If you guess right every time</strong>, the execution will never have to stop.<br>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<strong>If you guess wrong too often</strong>, you spend a lot of time stalling, rolling back, and restarting.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>This is branch prediction. I admit it's not the best analogy since the train could just signal the direction with a flag. But in computers, the processor doesn't know which direction a branch will go until the last moment.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>So how would you strategically guess to minimize the number of times that the train must back up and go down the other path? You look at the past history! If the train goes left 99% of the time, then you guess left. If it alternates, then you alternate your guesses. If it goes one way every 3 times, you guess the same...</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong><em>In other words, you try to identify a pattern and follow it.</em></strong> This is more or less how branch predictors work.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Most applications have well-behaved branches. So modern branch predictors will typically achieve &gt;90% hit rates. But when faced with unpredictable branches with no recognizable patterns, branch predictors are virtually useless.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Further reading: <a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branch_predictor[1;35m\"[0m[31m>[1;35m\"[0m[31mBranch predictor[1;35m\"[0m[31m article on Wikipedia</a>.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<h2>As hinted from above, the culprit is this if-statement:</h2>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>if (data[c] &gt;= 128)[1;35m\n[0m[31m    sum += data[c];[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Notice that the data is evenly distributed between 0 and 255. [1;35m\n[0m[31mWhen the data is sorted, roughly the first half of the iterations will not enter the if-statement. After that, they will all enter the if-statement.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>This is very friendly to the branch predictor since the branch consecutively goes the same direction many times.[1;35m\n[0m[31mEven a simple saturating counter will correctly predict the branch except for the few iterations after it switches direction.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>Quick visualization:</strong></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>T = branch taken[1;35m\n[0m[31mN = branch not taken[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31mdata[] = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ... 126, 127, 128, 129, 130, ... 250, 251, 252, ...[1;35m\n[0m[31mbranch = N  N  N  N  N  ...   N    N    T    T    T  ...   T    T    T  ...[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m       = NNNNNNNNNNNN ... NNNNNNNTTTTTTTTT ... TTTTTTTTTT  (easy to predict)[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>However, when the data is completely random, the branch predictor is rendered useless because it can't predict random data.[1;35m\n[0m[31mThus there will probably be around 50% misprediction. (no better than random guessing)</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>data[] = 226, 185, 125, 158, 198, 144, 217, 79, 202, 118,  14, 150, 177, 182, 133, ...[1;35m\n[0m[31mbranch =   T,   T,   N,   T,   T,   T,   T,  N,   T,   N,   N,   T,   T,   T,   N  ...[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m       = TTNTTTTNTNNTTTN ...   (completely random - hard to predict)[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>So what can be done?</strong></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>If the compiler isn't able to optimize the branch into a conditional move, you can try some hacks if you are willing to sacrifice readability for performance.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Replace:</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>if (data[c] &gt;= 128)[1;35m\n[0m[31m    sum += data[c];[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>with:</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>int t = (data[c] - 128) &gt;&gt; 31;[1;35m\n[0m[31msum += ~t &amp; data[c];[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>This eliminates the branch and replaces it with some bitwise operations.</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><sub>(Note that this hack is not strictly equivalent to the original if-statement. But in this case, it's valid for all the input values of <code>data[]</code>.)</sub></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>Benchmarks: Core i7 920 @ 3.5 GHz</strong></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>C++ - Visual Studio 2010 - x64 Release</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>//  Branch - Random[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 11.777[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branch - Sorted[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 2.352[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branchless - Random[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 2.564[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branchless - Sorted[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 2.587[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Java - Netbeans 7.1.1 JDK 7 - x64</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<pre><code>//  Branch - Random[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 10.93293813[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branch - Sorted[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 5.643797077[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branchless - Random[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 3.113581453[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m//  Branchless - Sorted[1;35m\n[0m[31mseconds = 3.186068823[1;35m\n[0m[31m</code></pre>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>Observations:</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<strong>With the Branch:</strong> There is a huge difference between the sorted and unsorted data.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<strong>With the Hack:</strong> There is no difference between sorted and unsorted data.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li>In the C++ case, the hack is actually a tad slower than with the branch when the data is sorted.</li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>A general rule of thumb is to avoid data-dependent branching in critical loops. (such as in this example)</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<hr>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p><strong>Update :</strong></p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li><p>GCC 4.6.1 with <code>-O3</code> or <code>-ftree-vectorize</code> on x64 is able to generate a conditional move. So there is no difference between the sorted and unsorted data - both are fast.</p></li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li><p>VC++ 2010 is unable to generate conditional moves for this branch even under <code>/Ox</code>.</p></li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li><p>Intel Compiler 11 does something miraculous. It <a href=[1;35m\"[0m[31m//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loop_interchange[1;35m\"[0m[31m>interchanges the two loops</a>, thereby hoisting the unpredictable branch to the outer loop. So not only is it immune the mispredictions, it is also twice as fast as whatever VC++ and GCC can generate! In other words, ICC took advantage of the test-loop to defeat the benchmark...</p></li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m<li><p>If you give the Intel Compiler the branchless code, it just out-right vectorizes it... and is just as fast as with the branch (with the loop interchange).</p></li>[1;35m\n[0m[31m</ul>[1;35m\n[0m[31m[1;35m\n[0m[31m<p>This goes to show that even mature modern compilers can vary wildly in their ability to optimize code...</p>[1;35m\n[0m[31m    </div>[1;31m"[0m[31m[0m}
